Imagine a very long Web page with many sections (e.g., specifications on a single HTML page). If the user requests a specific section (e.g. page.html#section7), what would happen if the Web server streamed this section first, then the others?
Stream order:
1. HTML document start until <body>
2. HTML for section 7
3. HTML for sections 1, 2, 3, etc.
The browser would then ensure to insert sections 1 to 6 *above* section 7 on the web page.
Is that clear? Could that be useful?
What I want to achieve is to have the rendering of the linked section (#section7) as fast as possible without having to reimplement anything with JavaScript. I just want to have a very long HTML document, but with the rendering of linked sections as fast as possible. This should work with HTML.
The content could be streamed in this way, and then the browser would inject each <contents> into its <div>.
<div id="sec1"></div>
<div id="sec2"></div>
etc.
<div id="sec7">section 7…</div>
<contents for="sec1">section 1…</contents>
<contents for="sec2">section 2…</contents>
etc.
Ca would be streamed in disarray, but the browser would assemble the HTML document as if it were streamed in order.
@user22 You can reorganize the documents like that even without JS. You cannot use the URL's hash part if you want the server to do something, but you can use query string parameters to indicate to the server which section you want to see first. To reorganize the parts, you have the choice between:
1. Using cascading stylesheets
2. Using a template with placeholders
@user23 Yes. The problem is that the visual order (what the user sees) does not correspond to the DOM order. It would be useful to have an HTML feature that allows streaming out of order, and the browser would rearrange the DOM content afterwards.
But the approach using placeholders seems promising. I'll try.
@user22 oh, you want the browser to correct the DOM order?
@user23 Yes, that's the idea. Section 7 would be streamed first only to allow the user to see it as soon as possible. It would be great if it could do it without affecting the DOM order, so that the browser can ensure that the resulting DOM order corresponds to the visual order.
In other words, stream section 7 first, but make it so that the final result (DOM and visual) is as if all sections had been streamed in order.
@user22 @user23 Have a look at PHOOOS without JS: https://github.com/niutech/phooos
